09:18.475 --> 09:21.435
So you grew up in New Jersey.

09:21.436 --> 09:24.897
How did you find your way to Okinawa?

09:24.898 --> 09:28.901
Well, my mom was from here. My dad was in the Navy.

09:28.902 --> 09:30.903
Mm-hm. -He was stationed here.

09:30.904 --> 09:34.323
Met my mom and wound up back in New Jersey

09:34.324 --> 09:36.116
because that's where my dad was from, Paterson.

09:36.117 --> 09:39.119
And I was born and raised there.

09:39.120 --> 09:44.624
The school I went to was
predominantly Caucasian kids.

09:44.625 --> 09:47.920
There wasn't many Asian-Americans at all.

09:47.921 --> 09:49.713
Right. -And I always had

09:49.714 --> 09:53.675
this kind of, like, identity complex.

09:53.676 --> 09:56.178
There would be, like, times where people would come

09:56.179 --> 09:58.514
to the house. They'd say,
"Oh, where's your mom from?

09:58.515 --> 10:00.974
"- Is she from China?" -Oh, God, right.

10:00.975 --> 10:03.769
Open the refrigerator and there
would be some weird food.

10:03.770 --> 10:06.439
"Hey, what's that?" Every time I heard that,

10:06.440 --> 10:09.400
I was like, wow, am I, like, am I different?

10:09.401 --> 10:11.735
So one day my mom says

10:11.736 --> 10:14.572
we're going back to Okinawa on a family trip.

10:14.573 --> 10:16.407
I was 17 years old. -You'd never been

10:16.408 --> 10:18.075
up to that point? -No, but when I got off

10:18.076 --> 10:20.578
the plane, I don't know what it was.

10:20.579 --> 10:24.582
It was like, I'm here, this is my home.

10:24.583 --> 10:28.961
Being able to connect to my
heritage, I felt something.

10:28.962 --> 10:31.880
I was like, wow, I belong here.

10:31.881 --> 10:35.008
How about the food? What was in that refrigerator?

10:35.009 --> 10:39.054
Because I know a lot of kids who
grew up with that same sort

10:39.055 --> 10:42.266
of uncertainty

10:42.267 --> 10:44.726
when they brought their friends home from school

10:44.727 --> 10:47.146
to their house and opened the refrigerator.

10:47.147 --> 10:51.942
You know, kimchee, or cabbage, or fish sauce.

10:51.943 --> 10:54.278
They were aware of it when
they visited their friends.

10:54.279 --> 10:56.071
And they were acutely uncomfortable with it

10:56.072 --> 10:59.199
when their friends came over.
Man, have things changed,

10:59.200 --> 11:01.785
as far as attitudes,

11:01.786 --> 11:05.456
pretty much the engine of the new American cuisine,

11:05.457 --> 11:07.833
are kids with childhoods like yours.

11:07.834 --> 11:11.044
I don't mean what's hip, what's the next new thing.

11:11.045 --> 11:16.425
I mean, literally redefining
what is American cuisine.

11:16.426 --> 11:18.636
Let's put it this way.

11:18.637 --> 11:22.264
The central irony of this story is that, you know,

11:22.265 --> 11:24.892
your mom would have been, like, hipster hero.

11:28.104 --> 11:29.980
<i>Still another American invasion</i>

11:29.981 --> 11:32.690
<i>in the Pacific. The objective is Okinawa,</i>

