17:51.445 --> 17:54.031
<i>And its even more vicious cousin, kobudo,</i>

17:54.032 --> 17:56.909
<i>a form that uses farm and fishing tools</i>

17:56.910 --> 17:58.869
<i>to lethal effect.</i>

17:58.870 --> 18:01.079
<i>Hard and soft. Balance.</i>

18:01.080 --> 18:06.125
<i>For everything soft, there must be something hard.</i>

18:06.126 --> 18:09.462
<i>Goju-ryu is one of the main
traditional styles of karate,</i>

18:09.463 --> 18:14.634
<i>featuring a combination of
hard and soft techniques.</i>

18:14.635 --> 18:17.971
<i>"Go" means hard linear attacks.</i>

18:17.972 --> 18:20.766
<i>Closed hand strikes and kicks.</i>

18:20.767 --> 18:23.894
<i>"Ju" means soft, open hand, circular,</i>

18:23.895 --> 18:27.899
<i>blocking, sweeping, and takedown moves.</i>

18:32.653 --> 18:37.783
<i>Sensei Tesuhiro Hokama is a
legendary master of goju-ryu.</i>

18:37.784 --> 18:41.160
<i>People come from all over the
world to study at his dojo.</i>

18:41.161 --> 18:44.874
<i>And the training they get is hardcore.</i>

18:55.301 --> 18:58.053
<i>I've been invited to watch Hokama Sensei's</i>

18:58.054 --> 19:01.723
<i>students warm up.</i>

19:01.724 --> 19:06.104
<i>Let me repeat: this is only the warm-up.</i>

19:10.524 --> 19:13.027
That does not look like fun.

19:14.194 --> 19:16.029
<i>The exercises are designed</i>

19:16.030 --> 19:18.323
<i>to repeatedly punish your hands and feet,</i>

19:18.324 --> 19:19.950
<i>building up stronger, larger,</i>

19:19.951 --> 19:23.120
<i>more protective deposits around the bones,</i>

19:23.121 --> 19:25.330
<i>basically weaponizing even your weakest</i>

19:25.331 --> 19:30.877
<i>and smallest extremities,
and it hurts even to watch.</i>

19:30.878 --> 19:33.506
Ooh.

19:36.676 --> 19:39.260
This is bad.

19:39.261 --> 19:42.639
<i>James Pankovich, Brit and black belt</i>

19:42.640 --> 19:46.434
<i>in shorin-ryu karate, moved to Okinawa in 2009</i>

19:46.435 --> 19:50.147
<i>to study budo, or the way of martial arts.</i>

19:50.148 --> 19:52.858
<i>He acts as translator for most of the karate sensei</i>

19:52.859 --> 19:54.526
<i>on the island.</i>

19:54.527 --> 19:57.362
<i>Earlier I met James and Hokama Sensei</i>

19:57.363 --> 20:01.282
<i>at Makishi Public Market, in
Okinawa's largest city, Naha.</i>

20:01.283 --> 20:04.537
That's the tasty one. We'll take that one.

20:05.788 --> 20:09.125
What are these? -These are puffer fish.

20:15.422 --> 20:18.133
So we got some deep-fried fish for us.

20:18.134 --> 20:20.593
<i>Gurukun, the unofficial national fish</i>

20:20.594 --> 20:25.348
<i>of Okinawa, and porcupine fish,
both battered and deep-fried.</i>

20:25.349 --> 20:26.307
They're gonna do sashimi.

20:26.308 --> 20:27.726
<i>Okinawans eat just about</i>

20:27.727 --> 20:29.853
<i>any kind of fish sashimi style.</i>

20:29.854 --> 20:31.897
<i>For us, snapper and parrotfish.</i>

20:31.898 --> 20:34.733
And lobster. <i>-'Cause one must,</i>

20:34.734 --> 20:37.652
<i>served raw and still twitching in the shell.</i>

20:37.653 --> 20:38.987
We're gonna get some sea grapes as well.

20:38.988 --> 20:41.447
Good, good, that's super traditional.

20:41.448 --> 20:43.909
<i>Sea grapes, the classic regional side dish</i>

20:43.910 --> 20:46.036
<i>dressed in rice vinegar.</i>

20:46.037 --> 20:50.665
<i>What you buy downstairs from
vendors, for a small fee,</i>

20:50.666 --> 20:53.544
<i>restaurants will cook it for you upstairs.</i>

20:59.175 --> 21:01.761
Wow.

21:04.555 --> 21:07.432
Wow.

21:07.433 --> 21:12.729
So, Okinawa's most famous
export, perhaps, is karate.

21:12.730 --> 21:15.273
Uh-huh. -When most of us think

21:15.274 --> 21:19.485
of karate, we think of striking. Exclusively.

21:19.486 --> 21:22.739
Is that an accurate representation

21:22.740 --> 21:25.158
of what you're doing? -The
basis of Okinawan karate

21:25.159 --> 21:29.704
is that it was used primarily as a defensive art.

21:29.705 --> 21:31.539
In other words, being able to, you know,

21:31.540 --> 21:34.667
control and subdue the opponent.

21:34.668 --> 21:37.170
Usually if you could, in a humane way,

21:37.171 --> 21:39.672
but then if you had to finish them,

21:39.673 --> 21:41.299
then you had the ability to finish them.

21:41.300 --> 21:43.135
The striking is important,

21:43.136 --> 21:45.637
but a lot of the technique is not about striking.

21:45.638 --> 21:47.680
It's about submission techniques.

21:47.681 --> 21:51.268
Some of that is to do with
kyushu, attacking nervepoints.

21:51.269 --> 21:53.478
And Hokama Sensei, in particular,

21:53.479 --> 21:58.150
is extremely skilled at dealing with, you know,

21:58.151 --> 22:01.319
bigger, stronger opponents. -Human engineering.

22:01.320 --> 22:03.488
Very important.

22:03.489 --> 22:07.075
Point, point, point, point, point,

22:07.076 --> 22:10.036
Point, point, point, point,

22:10.037 --> 22:13.414
then this point.

22:13.415 --> 22:19.254
No... No... open.

22:19.255 --> 22:22.048
<i>The demonstration of Hokama Sensei's open-hand</i>

22:22.049 --> 22:27.513
<i>kyushu technique becomes a
little too real for my taste.</i>

22:30.141 --> 22:31.599
Awful.

22:31.600 --> 22:35.312
<i>Human engineering with a terrifying logic,</i>

22:35.313 --> 22:37.897
<i>one attacks the weak point.</i>

22:37.898 --> 22:39.774
<i>All I know how to do in this situation, by the way,</i>

22:39.775 --> 22:43.569
<i>is pull guard and look for
something to choke or lock.</i>

22:43.570 --> 22:46.239
<i>Nope. Apparently, they don't know</i>

22:46.240 --> 22:48.616
<i>what tapping out means here. I was tapping</i>

22:48.617 --> 22:50.576
<i>like Western goddamn Union.</i>

22:50.577 --> 22:53.412
<i>I thought he was going to
push that 71-year-old finger</i>

22:53.413 --> 22:55.165
<i>right into my brain pan.</i>

22:55.166 --> 22:58.210
There was a saying in the old
days if there was a fight

22:58.211 --> 23:02.547
happening somewhere in town,
people would go have a look

23:02.548 --> 23:04.549
and they'd say, are they fighting

23:04.550 --> 23:07.635
with fists or open hands? If
they're fighting with fists,

23:07.636 --> 23:09.554
they'd say, don't bother, it's an amateur fight.

23:09.555 --> 23:12.015
If they were fighting with open hands,

23:12.016 --> 23:13.517
they knew they were masters.

23:21.275 --> 23:23.484
<i>On the eastern coast of Okinawa</i>

23:23.485 --> 23:25.778
<i>Yanks enter the village of Kin.</i>

23:25.779 --> 23:29.074
<i>The U.S. military came ashore in 1945,</i>

23:29.075 --> 23:33.619
<i>and to Okinawans, it must
seem like they never left.</i>

23:33.620 --> 23:39.458
<i>Today, there are roughly 30,000
troops stationed on the island.</i>

23:39.459 --> 23:42.837
<i>Put that many Americans in
a place, especially young,</i>

23:42.838 --> 23:45.798
<i>mostly male Americans, many of them homesick,</i>

23:45.799 --> 23:48.676
<i>and it tends to change the environment.</i>

23:48.677 --> 23:51.764
♪

23:56.394 --> 24:00.939
<i>Kintown, just outside of
Naha, right by Camp Hansen,</i>

24:00.940 --> 24:03.524
<i>one of the larger bases.</i>

24:03.525 --> 24:04.943
<i>Yanks have fought inch by inch</i>

24:04.944 --> 24:06.403
<i>to conquer this island.</i>

24:06.404 --> 24:08.613
<i>Kin is a small slice of Americana.</i>

24:08.614 --> 24:13.910
<i>Both the mainstream American
and its dark underbelly.</i>

24:13.911 --> 24:15.954
<i>The Okinawans have made the kind of adjustments</i>

24:15.955 --> 24:17.789
<i>that people do when saddled with neighbors</i>

24:17.790 --> 24:20.583
<i>like thousands of Marines,
and sometime in the '80s,</i>

24:20.584 --> 24:23.753
<i>adjusted food as we knew it to this,</i>

24:23.754 --> 24:29.466
<i>a mutant classic: taco rice.</i>

24:29.467 --> 24:33.054
Taco and rice. That's taco rice.

24:33.055 --> 24:36.142
Wow. -It's big.

24:40.854 --> 24:43.022
Is this chili sauce or ketchup?

24:43.023 --> 24:45.442
It's original taco. -Oh, it's taco sauce.

24:45.443 --> 24:49.321
Taco rice sauce. It's a bit spicy.

24:49.322 --> 24:52.865
Oh, good. -But not super spicy.

24:52.866 --> 24:55.410
<i>Vivian Takushi has lived in both the U.S.</i>

24:55.411 --> 24:58.579
<i>and Okinawa, and her aunt, Sumiko,</i>

24:58.580 --> 25:01.207
<i>an entertainer who began singing in American bases</i>

25:01.208 --> 25:02.459
<i>after the war.</i>

25:02.460 --> 25:04.378
Wow, that's good.

25:06.672 --> 25:09.424
<i>There are dueling claims as to how taco rice</i>

25:09.425 --> 25:11.592
<i>might have morphed into existence,</i>

25:11.593 --> 25:15.305
<i>but Saluri Shima Bakudo is certain.</i>

25:15.306 --> 25:17.765
<i>In the 1980s American servicemen introduced</i>

25:17.766 --> 25:19.934
<i>the standard taco to Okinawans,</i>

25:19.935 --> 25:22.687
<i>and her grandfather, Matsuzo Gibo,</i>

25:22.688 --> 25:24.356
<i>decided to tweak them,</i>

25:24.357 --> 25:26.523
<i>dumping the fillings straight onto rice</i>

25:26.524 --> 25:28.360
<i>for the late-night crowd of Marines</i>

25:28.361 --> 25:29.735
<i>coming back from the bars.</i>

25:29.736 --> 25:32.322
<i>This unholy, greasy, starchy,</i>

25:32.323 --> 25:34.573
<i>probably really unhealthy delight,</i>

25:34.574 --> 25:38.036
<i>a booze mop turned classic, caught on big-time,</i>

25:38.037 --> 25:41.414
<i>for both Americans missing home and locals.</i>

25:41.415 --> 25:45.751
So I consider myself a pretty pro-military guy,

25:45.752 --> 25:50.215
but why are the Marines here?

25:50.216 --> 25:53.385
I like marines, but, you know,
I'm not Robert McNamara.

25:53.386 --> 25:56.054
But it seems to me, if you go to war with China,

25:56.055 --> 25:58.056
sending in the Marines is probably not

25:58.057 --> 25:59.391
what you're gonna be doing.

25:59.392 --> 26:01.059
People of your generation,

26:01.060 --> 26:02.435
what do you think the attitude is

26:02.436 --> 26:04.354
towards the military bases?

26:04.355 --> 26:07.899
As long as we're not living near the base,

26:07.900 --> 26:10.235
it doesn't affect us that much.

26:10.236 --> 26:12.653
Near the base, it makes a difference.

26:12.654 --> 26:14.113
Right. I mean, near...

26:14.114 --> 26:17.367
It... you know right away.

26:17.368 --> 26:21.538
Tattoo parlors, strip clubs, vape shops.

26:21.539 --> 26:26.335
And also, you know, it's very loud.
That's a big issue.

26:28.045 --> 26:31.964
Tourism is probably the future of Okinawa. Yes?

26:31.965 --> 26:35.093
I mean, beautiful weather. Beaches.

26:35.094 --> 26:39.556
If the bases leave, it's going
to be big hotels and resorts

26:39.557 --> 26:41.891
and golf courses. Which is worse?

26:41.892 --> 26:44.727
Chinese tourists or American Marines?

26:44.728 --> 26:49.857
I'll stick with the Marines. -

26:49.858 --> 26:51.777
Semper fi.

26:54.988 --> 26:57.865
<i>Not everybody here agrees with Vivian,</i>

26:57.866 --> 27:01.994
<i>by a long shot. Okinawans may
be easygoing and laid back,</i>

27:01.995 --> 27:04.122
<i>but the island is also a relative hot bed</i>

27:04.123 --> 27:07.459
<i>of political activism, largely inspired or provoked</i>

27:07.460 --> 27:10.211
<i>by what Okinawans see as high-handed treatment</i>

27:10.212 --> 27:12.755
<i>from a central government with different cultural</i>

27:12.756 --> 27:15.550
<i>and historical traditions, who don't consider</i>

27:15.551 --> 27:17.552
<i>their needs or priorities.</i>

27:17.553 --> 27:21.097
<i>Their hugely disproportionate shouldering</i>

27:21.098 --> 27:25.184
<i>of the U.S. military presence
for the entire country.</i>

27:25.185 --> 27:28.563
<i>Currently there are close to
30 military installations</i>

27:28.564 --> 27:32.400
<i>on Okinawa, and even though
it's one of the smallest</i>

27:32.401 --> 27:35.278
<i>Japanese prefectures in terms of livable area,</i>

27:35.279 --> 27:37.196
<i>they accommodate more than half</i>

27:37.197 --> 27:40.699
<i>of the foreign military presence.</i>

27:40.700 --> 27:45.037
<i>Even more problematic, much
of Okinawa's arable land</i>

27:45.038 --> 27:47.499
<i>suitable for farming on an island whose whole</i>

27:47.500 --> 27:50.042
<i>traditional identity was built around farming</i>

27:50.043 --> 27:52.921
<i>is eaten up by military bases.</i>

27:58.511 --> 28:01.387
The military base issue, is this more important

28:01.388 --> 28:03.139
for older people or younger people?

28:03.140 --> 28:05.682
- It's for older people.
- It's for the older people.

28:05.683 --> 28:09.479
Yes. So when you actually go to
a place where they have, like,

28:09.480 --> 28:13.149
a protest going on, I will say
over 80 percent of the people

28:13.150 --> 28:18.237
- are all retired persons.
- Why do you think that is?

28:18.238 --> 28:23.284
This is only my opinion, but Japanese imperial army

28:23.285 --> 28:26.120
did a lot of brutal stuff on this island

28:26.121 --> 28:29.040
and war never ended for some people.

28:29.041 --> 28:31.376
And the feelings that they got suppressed,

28:31.377 --> 28:33.919
all of a sudden, after they retired,

28:33.920 --> 28:36.797
they kind of burst and they wanted to kind of...

28:36.798 --> 28:38.633
Act out. -Act out.

28:38.634 --> 28:41.594
<i>This is Keji Yota,</i>

28:41.595 --> 28:43.179
<i>he's an Okinawan farmer,</i>

28:43.180 --> 28:45.723
<i>and this is Nishimachi,</i>

28:45.724 --> 28:48.685
<i>a small noodle shop that
bears only the owner's name</i>

28:48.686 --> 28:51.938
<i>and serves only Okinawan-style soba.</i>

28:53.148 --> 28:56.067
<i>Pork belly or ribs is the meat.</i>

28:56.068 --> 28:58.695
<i>The broth a mix of fish, chicken, pork,</i>

28:58.696 --> 29:01.113
<i>and vegetable stocks.</i>

29:01.114 --> 29:03.199
<i>Okinawan soba differs greatly</i>

29:03.200 --> 29:05.451
<i>from what we know from the mainland.</i>

29:05.452 --> 29:07.953
<i>They use wheat noodles instead of buckwheat,</i>

29:07.954 --> 29:11.332
<i>a nod perhaps to the spaghetti
eating Marines they lived with</i>

29:11.333 --> 29:13.000
<i>all these years.</i>

29:13.001 --> 29:15.461
<i>Garnishes are spring onion, fish cake</i>

29:15.462 --> 29:18.214
<i>and slices of omelet. Add your pickled ginger,</i>

29:18.215 --> 29:22.176
<i>and togarashi hot sauce, and hoo-rah.</i>

29:22.177 --> 29:26.514
It seems the anti-base sentiment also coincides

29:26.515 --> 29:29.183
with an anti-central government sentiment.

29:29.184 --> 29:32.061
You do bear a hugely disproportionate

29:32.062 --> 29:36.023
burden of bases. Isn't some
activism called for here?

29:36.024 --> 29:40.612
I think the young generation
should decide what to do

29:40.613 --> 29:43.864
for our future instead of the
old people just fighting

29:43.865 --> 29:46.825
for their beliefs.

29:46.826 --> 29:51.997
To me, I really feel a strong need to forgive.

29:51.998 --> 29:54.876
Mm-hm. -And then forget.

29:57.421 --> 30:00.881
<i>Long before the war, the Americans arrived.</i>

30:00.882 --> 30:03.760
<i>Long before the Satsuma invaded from the mainland,</i>

30:03.761 --> 30:07.513
<i>Okinawa was a kingdom. The Ryukyu Kingdom.</i>

30:07.514 --> 30:10.642
<i>A prosperous and peaceful island chain</i>

30:10.643 --> 30:12.351
<i>with no standing army.</i>

30:12.352 --> 30:16.855
<i>They were farmers, traders,
and necessarily diplomats</i>

30:16.856 --> 30:20.610
<i>whose eyes, more often than
not, looked west to China</i>

30:20.611 --> 30:23.862
<i>rather than to the more isolated mainland.</i>

30:23.863 --> 30:26.574
<i>While Japan as it existed then was isolationist,</i>

30:26.575 --> 30:28.701
<i>racially and ethnically, culturally,</i>

30:28.702 --> 30:32.455
<i>and in every other way, the Ryukyu Kingdom</i> was not.

30:32.456 --> 30:36.250
<i>They were more open, more multicultural,</i>

30:36.251 --> 30:40.087
<i>more used to and predisposed to
dealing with the outside world</i>

30:40.088 --> 30:42.633
<i>and its influences.</i>

30:44.343 --> 30:46.803
<i>Today, just a short ferry
ride from the main island,</i>

30:46.804 --> 30:51.223
<i>a sense, a feeling of that
long-gone empire remains.</i>

30:51.224 --> 30:56.020
<i>Kumejima is a small island that
has been largely untouched</i>

30:56.021 --> 30:57.480
<i>by the changes in the world.</i>

30:57.481 --> 31:03.486
<i>People farm and fish as they always did.</i>

31:03.487 --> 31:07.990
The war never came here? -No.

31:07.991 --> 31:11.536
<i>This is Bunshiro Nagame and Yohina Tomohiro,</i>

31:11.537 --> 31:14.913
<i>Kumejima residents and friends of James.</i>

31:14.914 --> 31:18.167
They suffered very little damage in the war.

31:18.168 --> 31:22.673
And no military bases. No American presence.

31:28.303 --> 31:30.471
Up until '72, there was an American base.

31:30.472 --> 31:33.432
There was. -

31:33.433 --> 31:37.687
But then in '72, the base was taken away.

31:37.688 --> 31:42.024
Now nothing. -

31:42.025 --> 31:44.109
Only the Japanese self-defense forces now.

31:44.110 --> 31:46.904
What do people do here? Agriculture?

31:46.905 --> 31:49.532
Growing sugarcane. -I saw.

31:49.533 --> 31:54.662
Tourism. Fishing. -Fishing.

31:54.663 --> 31:58.332
Have there been attempts to
develop here and have the locals

31:58.333 --> 32:00.586
been able to resist that impulse?

32:03.963 --> 32:05.882
He's saying in Kumejima, they have rich lives.

32:05.883 --> 32:08.676
They have everything they need.
They have produce from the land,

32:08.677 --> 32:12.848
the sea. They don't need much else.

32:16.142 --> 32:18.603
<i>I've been invited to a beach barbecue,</i>

32:18.604 --> 32:20.396
<i>Kumejima style.</i>

32:20.397 --> 32:22.523
<i>Go big, or go home.</i>

32:22.524 --> 32:25.234
<i>To eat some fresh caught tuna that comes straight</i>

32:25.235 --> 32:31.031
<i>from the market to be butchered into sashimi.</i>

32:31.032 --> 32:33.910
<i>Also caught this morning, some
sea snails for the grill,</i>

32:33.911 --> 32:37.037
<i>and mozuku, seaweed which can be cooked,</i>

32:37.038 --> 32:40.583
<i>but today is enjoyed raw.</i>

32:40.584 --> 32:45.337
<i>And local prawns eaten either
raw or grilled, or both.</i>

32:45.338 --> 32:49.342
That looks awesome. Off with the head?

32:59.895 --> 33:02.396
<i>There's more. Local beef grilled</i>

33:02.397 --> 33:06.024
<i>and then tossed with moyashi,
seasoned bean sprouts.</i>

33:06.025 --> 33:10.363
<i>We will need our energy, it appears.</i>

